<p><em>Reviewed by an ICU RN | June 2026 | Updated for 2026 nurse licensing requirements</em></p>

<p>Nurses document everything — and not just in the EHR. A good physical log book keeps you organized between shifts, tracks continuing education hours, logs procedures for CRNA applications, and serves as a personal record the hospital's system doesn't capture.</p>

<p>After testing dozens of log books across specialties, here are the best for each type of nurse.</p>

<div class="highlight">
<strong>What makes a good nursing log book:</strong> Lay-flat binding (you're writing standing up), pre-formatted columns matched to your specialty, compact 6×9 size, and enough pages to last a full year.
</div>

<h2>Best for ICU Nurses</h2>

<div class="product">
<h3>ICU RN Patient Log Book — Critical Care Shift Record</h3>
<p class="stars">★★★★★</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Cardiovascular ICU, SICU, MICU, Neuro ICU nurses</p>
<p><strong>Columns:</strong> Date | Shift | Patient ID | Primary Diagnosis | Key Drips/Vents | Procedures | Handoff Notes</p>
<p><strong>Why it works:</strong> CRNA programs ask for documented proof of procedures (arterial lines, central lines, vasopressor management). A physical log gives you that record even if your hospital's EHR is locked after you leave.</p>
<p><strong>Pages:</strong> 120 log pages (enough for ~400 shifts at 3 entries/page)</p>
<p><strong>Price:</strong> $12.99 on Amazon KDP</p>
</div>

<div class="product">
<h3>CRNA School Application Procedure Log</h3>
<p class="stars">★★★★★</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> ICU nurses preparing to apply to CRNA programs</p>
<p><strong>Columns:</strong> Date | Procedure Type | # Performed | Supervision Level | Patient Complexity | Notes</p>
<p><strong>Why it works:</strong> CRNA programs want documented procedure counts. This book gives you a verifiable, organized record to present during interviews. Much better than trying to reconstruct numbers from memory.</p>
<p><strong>Tracked procedures:</strong> A-lines, central lines, PA caths, CRRT, vasopressors, vents, chest tubes</p>
<p><strong>Price:</strong> $13.99 on Amazon KDP</p>
</div>

